Dynamic Programming (DP) can feel hard at first, but most DP problems follow repeatable patterns. Below is a clear, practical method to solve DP problems in Python, with examples, templates, and mental checklists.
________________________________________
How to Solve DP Problems in Python (Step by Step)
What is DP?
Dynamic Programming is used when a problem has:
1.	Overlapping subproblems
2.	Optimal substructure (the solution depends on smaller solutions)
________________________________________
Golden Rule of DP
“Save results of subproblems so you don’t compute them again.”
________________________________________
Step by Step DP Thinking Process
✅ Step 1: Identify the Subproblem
Ask:
•	What is changing?
•	What parameters define a state?
Example
•	Fibonacci → subproblem = fib(n)
•	Knapsack → dp[i][w] = using first i items with capacity w
________________________________________
✅ Step 2: Write the Recurrence Relation
How does the current answer depend on smaller ones?
Example
fib(n) = fib(n−1) + fib(n−2)
________________________________________
✅ Step 3: Decide DP Type
Type	When to Use
1D DP	Sequential choices
2D DP	Two changing parameters
Memoization (Top Down)	Recursive intuition
Tabulation (Bottom Up)	Faster & iterative
________________________________________
✅ Step 4: Define Base Case
Smallest valid inputs.
fib(0) = 0
fib(1) = 1
________________________________________
✅ Step 5: Implement & Optimize
________________________________________
DP Implementation Styles in Python
1️⃣ Memoization (Top Down DP)
Fibonacci – Memoization
from functools import lru_cache

@lru_cache(None)
def fib(n):
    if n <= 1:
        return n
    return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2)
✅ Easy to write
❌ Recursive stack may overflow for very large inputs
________________________________________
2️⃣ Tabulation (Bottom Up DP)
Fibonacci – Tabulation
def fib(n):
    dp = [0] * (n + 1)
    dp[1] = 1

    for i in range(2, n + 1):
        dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2]

    return dp[n]
✅ Faster
✅ No recursion
✅ Preferred in interviews
________________________________________
Core DP Patterns (Very Important)
Pattern 1: 1D DP (Linear Problems)
Example: Climbing Stairs
def climbStairs(n):
    if n <= 2:
        return n

    dp = [0] * (n + 1)
    dp[1], dp[2] = 1, 2

    for i in range(3, n + 1):
        dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2]

    return dp[n]
________________________________________
Pattern 2: 2D DP (Grid / Choice Problems)
Example: 0/1 Knapsack
def knapsack(W, wt, val, n):
    dp = [[0] * (W + 1) for _ in range(n + 1)]

    for i in range(1, n + 1):
        for w in range(W + 1):
            if wt[i-1] <= w:
                dp[i][w] = max(
                    val[i-1] + dp[i-1][w - wt[i-1]],
                    dp[i-1][w]
                )
            else:
                dp[i][w] = dp[i-1][w]

    return dp[n][W]
________________________________________
Pattern 3: DP on Strings
Example: Longest Common Subsequence (LCS)
def lcs(text1, text2):
    m, n = len(text1), len(text2)
    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]

    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if text1[i-1] == text2[j-1]:
                dp[i][j] = 1 + dp[i-1][j-1]
            else:
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])

    return dp[m][n]
________________________________________
Pattern 4: DP + Decision Making
Example: House Robber
def rob(nums):
    if not nums:
        return 0
    if len(nums) == 1:
        return nums[0]

    dp = [0] * len(nums)
    dp[0] = nums[0]
    dp[1] = max(nums[0], nums[1])

    for i in range(2, len(nums)):
        dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], nums[i] + dp[i-2])

    return dp[-1]
________________________________________
Space Optimization Trick (Very Important)
Instead of:
dp[i] depends on dp[i-1], dp[i-2]
Use:
prev2, prev1 = 0, 1
for i in range(2, n+1):
    curr = prev1 + prev2
    prev2 = prev1
    prev1 = curr
✅ Reduces space from O(N) ➜ O(1)
________________________________________
How to Recognize a DP Problem?
Look for keywords:
•	“Maximum / Minimum”
•	“Number of ways”
•	“Longest / Shortest”
•	“Choose / Partition”
•	“Optimal”
________________________________________
Common Mistakes (Avoid These)
❌ Forgetting base cases
❌ Wrong state definition
❌ Off by one errors
❌ Using recursion without memoization
❌ Not checking constraints (TLE)
________________________________________
Interview DP Strategy
1.	Start with brute force
2.	Add memoization
3.	Convert to tabulation
4.	Optimize space (if asked)
________________________________________
Must Practice DP Problems
•	Fibonacci
•	Climbing Stairs
•	House Robber
•	Knapsack
•	Coin Change
•	LCS
•	LIS
•	Matrix Grid paths
________________________________________
If you want next: ✅ DP problem solving cheat sheet
✅ Daily DP practice roadmap (30 days)
✅ DP patterns classified by interview problems
✅ Explain any DP problem step by step
Just tell me which one 👌
Here’s a beginner friendly Dynamic Programming (DP) roadmap designed to take you from zero DP knowledge to interview ready, step by step. This roadmap assumes you’re using Python and already know basic loops, lists, and functions.
________________________________________
🧭 Dynamic Programming Roadmap for Beginners
Phase 0: Prerequisites (VERY IMPORTANT)
⏱️ Time: 2–3 days
Before DP, make sure you understand:
•	Python basics (if, loops, lists, functions)
•	Recursion
•	Time complexity (Big O basics)
✅ Practice:
•	Fibonacci (recursive)
•	Factorial
•	Binary search (recursive)
________________________________________
Phase 1: Understand DP Fundamentals
⏱️ Time: 2–3 days
What to Learn
•	What is Dynamic Programming?
•	Overlapping subproblems
•	Optimal substructure
•	Memoization vs Tabulation
Key Concept
DP = Recursion + Storing results
Practice Problems
•	Fibonacci (with memoization)
•	Climbing Stairs
✅ Goal:
Convert a recursive solution → memoized solution
________________________________________
Phase 2: 1D DP (Linear DP)
⏱️ Time: 4–5 days
Common Pattern
dp[i] = best result until index i
Topics
•	Fibonacci optimization
•	Climbing stairs
•	Min cost climbing stairs
•	House Robber
•	Decode Ways
Example Problems
•	House Robber
•	Maximum Subarray (Kadane’s Algorithm)
•	Jump Game
✅ Skills Gained:
•	Writing dp arrays
•	Understanding state transitions
•	Space optimization (O(1) DP)
________________________________________
Phase 3: DP on Arrays & Subsets
⏱️ Time: 5–6 days
Topics
•	Subset problems
•	0/1 Knapsack
•	Partition Equal Subset Sum
•	Target Sum
Pattern
dp[i][w] → considering first i elements with capacity w
✅ Problems to Solve:
•	0/1 Knapsack
•	Subset Sum
•	Coin Change (limited coins)
✅ Skills Gained:
•	2D DP
•	Decision-based DP
•	Table filling logic
________________________________________
Phase 4: DP on Strings
⏱️ Time: 5–6 days
Topics
•	Longest Common Subsequence (LCS)
•	Longest Palindromic Subsequence
•	Edit Distance
•	String matching using DP
Common DP Table
dp[i][j] = answer for first i chars and first j chars
✅ Must Do Problems:
•	LCS
•	Edit Distance
•	Longest Palindromic Subsequence
✅ Skills Gained:
•	Thinking in 2 dimensions
•	Character matching logic
________________________________________
Phase 5: Unbounded Knapsack Pattern
⏱️ Time: 3–4 days
Topics
•	Coin Change (unlimited coins)
•	Rod Cutting
•	Integer Break
Pattern Difference
•	Item can be reused
•	Transition stays in same row
✅ Problems:
•	Coin Change (minimum coins)
•	Coin Change (number of ways)
________________________________________
Phase 6: Grid / Matrix DP
⏱️ Time: 3–4 days
Topics
•	Unique Paths
•	Minimum Path Sum
•	Grid with obstacles
Pattern
dp[i][j] = from top + from left
✅ Problems:
•	Unique Paths
•	Minimum Path Sum
✅ Skills:
•	Grid movement DP
•	Boundary handling
________________________________________
Phase 7: Advanced DP Concepts (Optional for Beginners)
⏱️ Time: 7–10 days
Topics
•	DP with Bitmasking
•	DP on Trees
•	DP on Graphs
•	State compression
✅ Only if:
•	You are preparing for product based company interviews
________________________________________
Phase 8: DP Patterns Revision & Optimization
⏱️ Ongoing
Learn These Patterns
✅ Linear DP
✅ Choice based DP
✅ Knapsack pattern
✅ String DP
✅ Grid DP
Practice Strategy
•	Solve 1 problem/day
•	Rewrite solution without looking
•	Explain DP logic out loud
________________________________________
📅 Suggested 30 Day Beginner Plan
Week	Focus
Week 1	Recursion + DP basics
Week 2	1D DP + Subset DP
Week 3	String DP + Unbounded DP
Week 4	Grid DP + Revision
________________________________________
✅ How You Know You’re Good at DP
•	You can define the DP state quickly
•	You know what dp[i] means
•	You can convert recursion → tabulation
•	You recognize DP patterns instantly
________________________________________
🔑 Golden Advice for Beginners
•	Never jump directly to DP
•	Always start with brute force
•	Write recursion first
•	Then memoize
•	Then tabulate
________________________________________
